Anaheim Police Department

************************************************************************


A message was sent to you regarding record request #26-1844:

Dear Requestor,

&nbsp;

The Anaheim Police Department received your request dated February 25, 2026, wherein you have requested the following:

&nbsp;

...



GenPrime Fertility has had a Los Angeles location since 2024.

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records (dated from January 1, 2024 to the time this request is processed):

- All tips and 911 audios/transcripts made from the address 1808 W Lincoln Ave, Anaheim, CA 92801, or mentioning said address. Please include any subsequent CAD reports, incident reports, and investigative documents produced in connection to these calls.

- All body camera footage produced in any police responses to the address 1808 W Lincoln Ave, Anaheim, CA 92801.

I respectfully request that my request is expedited, given the newsworthiness and high-profile nature of abuse of the US fertility industry. This WSJ article highlights the issue: https://www.wsj.com/us-news/chinese-billionaires-surrogacy-pregnancy-7fdfc0c3. It mentions that Peter Thiel's family office "has backed a chain of IVF clinics across Southeast Asia and a recently opened branch in Los Angeles." This is GenPrime Fertility. I also respectfully request that documents are released on a rolling basis.

I am a news reporter for WIRED (wired.com), so the requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. Therefore, I request that any fees are waived. But in the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by email attachment if available.

If you need to contact me, you can reach me at&nbsp;caroline_haskins@wired.com, or here. Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.



...



The Anaheim Police Department has identified records responsive to your request and have been published to our NextRequest portal.

&nbsp;

Other record(s) you seek may be withheld from production if they fall within any of the following exemptions to the Public Records Act:

&nbsp;

·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Police investigatory records are generally exempt from disclosure pursuant to Government Code §7923.600(a);



·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Documents reflecting police techniques or "security procedures" are expressly exempt from disclosure pursuant to Government Code §7923.600(a);



·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Personal contact information is exempt from disclosure. [Government Code §7922.000];



·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;You are not the victim of the subject incident, nor have you provided evidence that you are an authorized representative thereof, and the report is exempt from disclosure pursuant to Government Code §7923.615(a);



·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Victims of certain types of crimes including sexual assault may request that their identity be withheld per Government Code §7923.615(a);



·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Juvenile information is confidential (Welfare and Institutions Code §§ 827 and 828);



·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The City does not possess a record that consists of the specific information that you have requested and has no duty to create a record that does not exist at the time of the request.&nbsp;Government Code §7920.530; Haynie v. Superior Court (2001) 26 Cal.4th 1061; 71 Ops.CalAtty.Gen. 235 (1988);



·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Items including, but not limited to Photos, Videos, 911 Audio, Body worn camera footage, etc. is considered evidence and is exempt from release, pursuant to Government Code §7923.600(a);



·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The records may be related to ongoing investigations and therefore are exempt from disclosure pursuant to Government Code §§7927.500, 7929.000, and 7923.600(a) (See also, Haynie v. Superior Court (2001) 26 Cal.4th 1061; Williams v. Superior Court (1993) 5 Cal.4th 337; Rivero v. Superior Court (1997) 54 Cal.App.4th 1048; Rackauckas v. Superior Court (2002) 104 Cal.App.4th 169; Commission on Peace Officer Standards and Training v. Superior Court (2007) 42 Cal.4th 278; New York Times v. Superior Court (1997) 52 Cal.App.4th 97; and 91 Ops. Cal.Atty.Gen. 11 (2008));&nbsp;



·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The subject investigation relates to potential criminal prosecution.&nbsp;Evidence gathered as part of a criminal investigation is by its nature confidential.&nbsp;Investigative files are therefore privileged so long as the need for confidentiality outweighs the benefits of disclosure in the particular case.&nbsp;County of Orange v Superior Court (Wu) (2000) 79 CA4th 759, 765, 768, 94 CR2d 261, 264, 266; Evidence Code section 1040(b).

&nbsp;



Without waiving the foregoing exemptions and subject to them, the Anaheim Police Department has identified records responsive to your request and have been published to our NextRequest portal.







&nbsp;

Sincerely,



ANAHEIM POLICE DEPARTMENT

RECORDS SECTION








